The evolution of all densities is depicted in figure 1, starting at MeV temperatures until now. The density fractions 





 are shown in this figure, where it is easy to see which of the Universe components dominates, fixing its expansion rate: first, radiation in the form of photons and neutrinos (radiation domination); then matter, which can be CDM, baryons and massive neutrinos at late times (matter domination); and finally, the cosmological constant density takes over at low z (typically 





).

Massive neutrinos are the only known particles that present a late transition from radiation to matter, when their density is clearly enhanced (upper solid lines in figure 1). Obviously, the contribution of massive neutrinos to the energy density in the non-relativistic limit is a function of the mass (or the sum of all masses for which 





), and the present value 





 could be of order unity for eV masses (see section 4).

The measurement of CMB anisotropies can be complemented by some data on the cosmological expansion at low redshift (





). The recent expansion history can be inferred from the luminosity of type-Ia supernovae, from the angular scale of baryon acoustic oscillations (BAO) reconstructed from the galaxy power spectrum at various redshifts, or from direct measurements of the current expansion rate 





 through nearby cepheids and supernovae.
